Part 1 - The Crime Analysis Overview¶

As Sedjaoui (2018, p.33) explains, ‘big data is the revolutionary word in today’s world because of its influence on several domains.’ This can range from government bodies to businesses trying to find the edge over their competitors. In this context, we will be using government provided data to explore claims made by the Ross Kemp documentary. The media likewise in 2019 appeared to agree with some of the statements with the BBC reporting that ‘Violent Crime recorded by police rises by 19%’ (BBC, 2019).

The aim of this report is to substantiate the many claims that were made in the aforementioned documentary. Whilst generic statements such as ‘Violent crime is increasing’ or ‘Crimes involving firearms are closely associated with drug offences’ are easy to digest for the general public, they may not tell the wider picture that the data shows. For example, is violent crime showing seasonal changes or is there no correlation? How strong is the relationship between crimes involving firearms and drug offences? As Hodeghatta and Nayak (2023, ch.1, section. 1.6) state, ‘having only programming skills along with statistical or mathematical knowledge can sometimes lead to proposing impractical suggestions.’ Therefore, I will use a carefully planned journey to validate the above claims.

Throughout this process, I will be using Apache Sparks through Azure IAAS to analyse the big data sets I have selected – Street Level Crime Data and LSOA_POP (population dataset). Through testing, I found that loading the data into Jupyter was quicker than via Blob Storage so will therefore be the method I choose. Once the dataset has been loaded, I will be using RDDs to initially filter the data. This will be violent crimes, drug offences, and I will be filtering the population data set to contain a sum of all the residents in a certain area. Like above, I found this quicker than if the data was loaded straight into a dataframe. These steps will be achieved through created functions.

From there, I will use a range of visualisations to attribute a pictorial representation of the different relationships. However, simple presenting this isn’t sufficient – as Nudurupari (2021, loc 189) explains, ‘the process of translating data into a pictorial representation (data visualisation)’ …’ makes it easier for the human mind to comprehend complex information’. Whilst this is true, it is important that machine learning models and statistics are both used as well to connect a numerical value that can show the strength of relationships. Once all these steps have been taken, I will then explain from my point of view the results of the analysis to highlight the degree to which I agree or disagree with the above claims.

Part 3 - Data Extraction and Filtering¶

Next, I will create a series of functions which will be passed to the text_rdd to filter down the different crimes needed. At this stage, I will not be filtering by date as I found combining that with the text filter at this stage increased the time to create the filtered RDD. The reason I will be eventually filtering by date is the fact that the documentary was released in September 2018. I therefore want to substantiate the claims made based on the data available at the time of recording. Moreover, post 2018 the coronavirus lockdowns would likely affect crime rates due to the ‘Stay at home’ message.

It is important to note that circa April 2013, the tag in the ‘Crime Type’ field was renamed to ‘Violence and Sexual Offences’. Therefore, both tags have been included in the function through an ‘or’ clause.

As determined in the specification, a ‘firearm incident’ is being categorised with a ‘Crime Type’ of ‘Possession of Weapons’ and an outcome of ‘Offender sent to prison’. Therefore an ‘and’ clause has been used to filter the data for this RDD.

I have finally created a ‘remove_after_last_space’ function. This will remove anything after a location name in the population dataset. For example, ‘Birmingham 003A’ will simply return ‘Birmingham’ to allow for clear analysis of claim 2 – ‘There are more firearm incidents per head in Birmingham than anywhere else in the UK.’ This will only be applied on the dataframe in the specific column related to a location (LSOA Name).

In [5]:
def contains_violent_crimes(line):
    line_lower = line.lower()
    return "violent crime" in line_lower or "violence and sexual offences" in line_lower

def contains_firearm_incidents(line):
    line_lower = line.lower()
    return "possession of weapons" in line_lower and "offender sent to prison" in line_lower

def contains_drug_incidents(line):
    line_lower = line.lower()
    return "drugs" in line.lower()

def remove_after_last_space(value):
    if not value:
        return "No Location Given"
    return value.rsplit(' ', 1)[0]

remove_space_udf = udf(remove_after_last_space, StringType())

vc_df = (violent_crime_df
        .select("MonthYear", "CrimeType")
        .where(violent_crime_df.MonthYear < "2018-10")
        .groupBy("MonthYear")
        .agg(count("CrimeType").alias("Total"))
        .orderBy("MonthYear"))

Part 4 - Design, Development and reasoning behind use of multiple visualization methods, statistics, and machine learning Models¶

Claim 1

When completing data visualisations for the first claim, I will be plotting the data as a timeseries to explore the changes in the data over time. Initially, I will be able to see if there is an upward, downward or lack of trend. From there, I will complete a seasonal decomposition which will highlight the trend, seasonal changes and any residual changes. It is worth noting that because the data is grouped by month, there will only be 12 plots per year. As Nielsen (2019) explains, 'with low sample size, false positives for unit roots are fairly common' and is something that should be considered when applying the resultant data to the machine learning model.

As seen from the above plot, there is a clear upward trend for violent crimes. However, it is worth remembering that the tag changed in circa April 2013 to 'Violence and sexual offences'. Questions could be asked about how data was reported before April 2013 in relation to sexual offences as this could have been under the 'Other crime' tag used during this time. This could be one explanation of the mostly upward trend of the above plot from this point onwards.

Despite this, there are seasonal changes occurring on a year by year basis. There are clear peaks in the summer months, especially in the summer of 2018. This can likely be attributed to the weather, people spending more time outdoors and large amounts of alcohol being consumed. There are various reports and articles linking the above such as by Dearden (2022) who interviewed a PCC explaining that with ‘people outside, you’ve got barbecues, street parties, people consuming more alcohol, spilling outside pubs and clubs. You are naturally going to see a crime spike and the hotter the weather gets the worse it is.’ Hambling’s (2019) article further substantiates this theory after exploring studies relating to temperature and violent crimes determining that ‘High temperatures make people more impulsive, and violent acts get committed literally in the heat of the moment’.

It is also worth noting the peak of Summer 2018 - this was during the 2018 World Cup in which England reached the semi-finals. Again, this can show a cause and effect relationship for the spike at this point – as the CPS (2022) explored ‘Data showed reported incidents increased by 26 percent if England play, 38 percent if England lose, and 11 percent the next day, win or lose’.

After taking all the above into account, there are clear seasonal patterns so a time series analysis needs to be conducted. As the above is non-stationary, it needs to be made stationary as Joseph(DATE) explains that stationarity is of great significance and is described as when the probability distribution remains the same at every point. Therefore, I will aim to create stationarity through a series of tests using the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test. I will complete this with a variety of data such as the raw data itself, the data detrended, 12-lag and 12-lag detrended.

In [70]:
def test_stationarity(timeseries, title): #stationarity function to be executed.
    plt.clf()
    rolmean = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=12).mean() 
    rolstd = pd.Series(timeseries).rolling(window=12).std()
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 4))
    ax.plot(timeseries, label= title)
    ax.plot(rolmean, label='rolling mean');
    ax.plot(rolstd, label='rolling std (x10)');
    ax.legend()
    plt.show()
In [71]:
def ADF_test(timeseries, dataDesc):
    print(' > Is the {} stationary ?'.format(dataDesc))
    dftest = adfuller(timeseries.dropna(), autolag='AIC')
    print('Test statistic = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[0]))
    print('P-value = {:.3f}'.format(dftest[1]))
    print('Critical values :')
    for k, v in dftest[4].items():
        print('\t{}: {} - The data is {} stationary with {}% confidence'.format(k, v, 'not' if v<dftest[0] else '', 100-int(k[:-1])))

Claim 2

When completing data visualisations for claim 2, I will be using a bar chart. This will allow for the clearest representation of the data and will be ordered from highest to lowest on a basis of firearm incidents per 5000 people to allow for a fair representation from different areas. I will be using black for the bars. As Kashyap (2020) explains, 'use of color in a visualisation should be to help disseminate key findings instead of being part of some sort of artistic endeavor'. Murray (2019) takes this further in saying that data can be turned from an 'unassuming visualization into an emotion-filled data story' which can lead to inaccurate results and conclusions being taken. After completing this visualisation, I will then plot a scatterplot to explore whether there is a relationship between other features such as average income rank, employment rank or IMD rank can play an impact on firearm incidents too.

Part 5 - Selection, application, and reasoning behind use of statistical analysis and multiple evaluation measures¶

For claim 1, I will be using ARIMA machine learning model to analyse the data. I will be using the best fit AIC – the lowest result – to then explore how this produces an accurate forecast in relation to the observed pattern. When exploring this, it is important that the KDE and N for the histogram are closely aligned in shape and height. Equally, the plots along the Q-Q should closely follow the line of best fit. Finally, in the correlogram, with the exception of ‘0’, the rest of the points should sit comfortably within the confidence level band shown.

After applying the most appropriate model, I will use this to explore the forecast for the time points inputted below. I will then create tables to highlight the upper and lower bounds, as well as the mean between these two values. Finally, I will be using a range of evaluative values to explore how well the model fits with the data.

For claim 2, I will be using the RMSE evaluator for linear regression to understand the performance of both models I have created.

For claim 3, I will be using clustering. This will identify clusters of locations for where there are the most firearm and drug offences. I will finally use a clustering evaluator to understand the centers of each cluster.

def timeseries_evaluation_metrics_func(y_train, y_test):
    def mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_true, y_pred):
        y_true, y_pred = np.array(y_true), np.array(y_pred)
        return np.mean(np.abs((y_true - y_pred) / y_true)) * 100

    print('Evaluation metric results:')
    print(f'MSE is: {metrics.mean_squared_error(y_train, y_test)}')
    print(f'MAE is: {metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_train, y_test)}')
    print(f'RMSE is: {np.sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_train, y_test))}')
    print(f'MAPE is: {mean_absolute_percentage_error(y_train, y_test)}')
    print(f'R2 is: {metrics.r2_score(y_train, y_test)}')

The above shows a large MAPE and low R2. Therefore, I will look at another model.

def runlr(trainDF, testDF, feature_cols):
    vecAssembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=feature_cols, outputCol="features")
    vecTrainDF = vecAssembler.transform(trainDF)
    lr = LinearRegression(featuresCol="features", labelCol="AvgIncomeRank")
    lrModel = lr.fit(vecTrainDF)
    pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[vecAssembler, lr])
    pipelineModel = pipeline.fit(trainDF)
    return pipelineModel.transform(testDF)

Part 6 - Detailed Analysis and consideration of the appropriateness of the solution for the initial problem¶

For each claim, I will consider the advantages, disadvantages and limitations of the methods used.

For the first claim, a time series analysis was used to understand the trends that were happening year on year and evaluating whether this could be used to accurately forecast future changes in violent crimes. The main disadvantage of the time series was how it wouldn't become stationary without significant differencing. Whilst an ok method to use, completing too much differencing can result in some of the key trends disappearing from the final results. Furthermore, as explored in the analysis of the time series, the bounds either side of the predicted mean offer substantial margins meaning an accurate forecast has not really been made. While I used 2 of the ARIMA models, more time could have been given to exploring better fits which would have resulted in a more accurate forecast. Despite this, some of the trends have been accurately mapped so a shorter time scale may reflect an accurate forecast.

For the second claim, the use of bar charts, while simple in effect, provided a clear visual representation of the data and showed how Birmingham does not have the highest amount of firearm incidents per head in the UK (changed to per 5000 throughout in this report). As Birmingham was the focal point, on reflection, writing a query which includes the top 50 and Birmingham would have perhaps been better suited. I would have liked to have included a chorograph to display this data however could not execute this effectively. This was the claim I had more issues with proving through statistics and machine learning models hence why I went down the route of creating a prediction model based on the different ranks to see the effect it had on firearm incidents.

For the third claim, the use of a scatterplot and correlative measures were effective in showing the correlation between drug offences and firearm incidents. It is worth noting as ___ explains that this does not guarantee causation between the two variables. As seen from the final analysis, there are 3 main clusters with a large focus on cluster 1 with an average of 10422 drug crimes and 62 firearm incidents. It should be worth noting that one of the clusters has a large number of locations within it, 273. Therefore, further clustering could take place. On top of this, further analysis could take place to analyse whether there is a connection between the locations within the different clusters and another variable such as income score explored through the model created in claim 2.

My final thought on the above is the use of grouping the data by the main location throughout(e.g. Birmingham instead of Birmingham 003A). I feel this made it easier to analyse the data by location especially for claims 2 and 3, however there may be certain relationships that weren't able to be analysed effectively due to this chosen route. The average income rank and employment rank for example had to be averaged to be able to be analysed in this way meaning lower ranked areas were combined with higher ranked areas. This is something that should also be considered throughout.

Overall, I feel that whilst I am able to justify the above claims, some of the above models, statistics and initial filtering could be changed to create improved analysis against the claims. Naturally, this will come with more practice and experience with similar datasets.

Evaluation and Conclusion¶

Claim 1 - Violent Crime is increasing

On the one hand, I agree with this statement. As seen from the initial plot of the data, there are increases on a year by year basis. However, this does not tell the full picture. When exploring the seasonal analysis, it is clear that there are changes within a year particularly around the Summer months. As explained above and covered by the media, the Summer months and accompanied weather results in people being outside more and increased levels of alcohol levels. This results in greater levels of violent crimes during the Summer months. The seasonal changes are not always consistent however.

Claim 2 - There are more firearms incidents per head in Birmingham than anywhere else in the UK.

I disagree with this statement. After completing the filtering and dividing the number of firearms by a location's population, City of London has the highest number of firearm incidents. As examined above, it should also be noted that the City of London also has one of the smallest populations as per the LSOA population dataset. Even if this were taken out of the situation, there are other locations which rank higher than Birmingham for firearm incidents. It should be noted however that Birmingham does have the highest number of firearm incidents in the UK when per head characteristics are not taken into account.

Claim 3 - Crimes involving firearms are closely associated with drugs offences

I agree with this statement. When completing the analysis of the relationship between drug offences and violent crimes, the Pearson Correlation showed a result of 0.839(3dp) showing a very strong correlation. There could also be room for further analysis such as exploring whether there is a relationship between the locations within the clusters and applying further features from the deprivation dataset.
